I&#39;d recommend not worrying about performance until it becomes a problem, unless high-performance is specifically a requirement. In particular, Linq can have some [performance costs][1], but is great for readability and should be used.

But your concern about readability is a good one. A few tips:

### [Single Responsibility Principle][2] 
try to identify specific responsibilities and encapsulate these into functions/classes as appropriate. In particular the responsibility of this block:

```csharp
            OldIncomeStructure structure = new OldIncomeStructure();
            structure.PersonId = personIncome.PersonId;
            foreach(var prijem in personIncome.Incomes)
            {
                switch (prijem.IncomeTemplateId)
                {
                    case 1:
                        structure.MainJob = prijem.Amount;
                        break;
                    case 2:
                        structure.SideJob = prijem.Amount;
                        break;
                    case 3:
                        structure.Maternity = prijem.Amount;
                        break;
                    case 4:
                        structure.Retirement = prijem.Amount;
                        break;
                    case 5:
                        structure.Other = prijem.Amount;
                        break;    
                }
            }
```

could be summed up as &quot;create a new `OldIncomeStructure` instance from a `PersonalIncome` instance&quot;. You could encapsulate this into a function as follows:

```csharp
public static OldIncomeStructure CreateOldIncomeStructure(PersonalIncome personIncome)
{
    // the above code
}
```

you can then get do something like

```csharp
var listOldPersonIncome = balance.IncomeOverview.PersonIncome.Select(p =&gt; CreateOldIncomeStructure(p)).ToList();
```

to replace the outer `foreach`.

### Naming

Take care of naming of variables/types, in particular I think the following substitutions would help readability:

* `OldIncomeStructure` -&gt; `LegacyIncome`
* `List&lt;PersonalIncome&gt; PersonIncome` -&gt; `List&lt;PersonalIncome&gt; PersonalIncomes`
* `var prijem` -&gt; `var income`

### Avoid ref parameters

`PopulateBalance` could instead be `GetBalance` and create/return a `Balance` object, rather than using `ref`

  [1]: https://mattwarren.org/2016/09/29/Optimising-LINQ/
  [2]: https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Single_responsibility_principle

