Here you are iterating through a length of The original Puzzle String but your are comparing the characters from the actual **word** to characters within the **puzzleDup** string. At first the **puzzleDup** variable will hold the original content of the actual Puzzle String but within the same loop you delete any found characters that will match a character from the **word** being tested. By doing this deletion it reduces the length of **puzzleDup** and because the **Puzzle String** will be longer than what **puzzleDup** will be the integer variable **j** will eventually go out of bounds of what **puzzleDup** is capable of handling therefore generating the **StringIndexOutOfBoundsException**. 

The bottom line....if you are going to be comparing **word** characters to **puzzleDup** characters and then modifying **puzzleDup** during the process then use **puzzleDup** in the loop declaration:

    for (int j = 0; j &lt; puzzleDup.length(); j++) {
