is not really all that effective unless the first character of **puzzleDup** will always be the character being compared to from the **word**. What is to happen if it&#39;s the 3rd character in **puzzleDup**? Do you then wipe out the first three characters contained within **puzzleDup**? What if one of the characters you just wiped out is needed for the next **word** character? I believe the idea here would be to remove **only** the specific character in **puzzleDup** that made the match to the current character of **word**. This line should then be:

    puzzleDup = puzzleDup.substring(0, j) + puzzleDup.substring(j + 1);

This line of code will remove from **puzzleDup** only the character that is equal to the character from the word currently being processed. This now leaves all other characters in **puzzleDup** to have the chance to be compared to. The entire inner loop should really look like this:

    for (int j = 0; j &lt; puzzleDup.length(); j++) {
